Opacity

Target IP: 10.10.97.62

Scanning


There are four TCP ports open on the target machine. I will start enumeration with the HTTP application as the SMB does not have any shares I can access.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this application. Viewing the source-code of this webpage does not reveal anything useful. I tried default credentials, but I had no luck either.


Doing a directory search against this host shows an interesting entry called /cloud.


Browsing to /cloud reveals the webpage above. It mentions External URL -- can I try possibly try RFI?


I saved a picture of the folder from the main webpage on my local machine. Then I started a Python HTTP server on port 8008. To upload the image, I provided the URL http://10.14.55.153:8008/folder.png. And this image was uploaded successfully, as shown above. I can browse to the URL above to access it. After five minutes, the uploaded image was removed by the server.

Exploitation


I tried a few different payloads, and I found one that works. I created a file called folder.php that contains the PHP Pentest Monkey reverse shell script. This file contains the magic bytes of GIF89a; at the beginning. I started a Python HTTP server on port 80 to handle the image request and another listener on port 8443 for the reverse shell connection.


After pressing the Upload Image button, I intercepted the request using Burpsuite. Then in the URL, I appended %0a.jpg, so the uploaded file would be folder.php instead of folder.php.jpg. This is done to bypass the filtering in place; otherwise, the POST request would be discarded by the server.


The file was uploaded successfully at http://10.10.97.62/cloud/images/folder.php because anything after %0a was discarded.


And now I have a reverse shell connection on port 8443. Now I have a foothold on the target machine.

Privilege Escalation


Running the command find / -writable -type f 2>/dev/null shows the interesting files above that the user www-data has access to. Maybe one of these files contain a password?


And bingo! The file login.php contains the password oncloud9. There is a user called sysadmin on this machine; maybe, I can spray this password against this user?


Using admin:oncloud9 against the login form at port 80 works, but not when trying to switch to this user.


I notice there is a backup.zip file inside backups. Is this achieved by a cronjob? I transferred this to my machine and checked the content and found the scripts.


I transferred pspy64 to the target machine and ran it. It looks like there is a cronjob. But I am unable to change it as www-data.


After finding nothing, I ran Linpeas. There is a KeePass file here. Maybe the user sysadmin has their password saved inside this file? I transferred this file to my machine and ran john on it to obtain the password hash. I managed to crack the password, but I will need to use KeePass to obtain the password inside it.


I opened the password file using KeePass application and used the password 741852963. Then I have access to the password of user sysadmin which is shown above.


And now I have access to the target machine as the user sysadmin by using the password saved inside the KeePass.


The cronjob script script.php contains the content above. It looks like it imports the backup.inc.php file inside lib. I am unable to change the script files directly. However, I can remove them and replace them with malicious one.


I put a PHP reverse shell script inside the zipData function at backup.inc.php. And I started a Python HTTP server on port 80 for this file transfer to the target machine.


I removed the original backup.inc.php file and replaced it with the malicious one. I also changed the file to be executable. To do this on the target machine, I used wget to download the malicious backup.inc.php using the Python HTTP server from my machine. Then I started a listener on port 8444, and received a root reverse shell connection after a few minutes. Now I have a root shell.
